---

## License structure of this project

This project uses a multi-component license structure. Each layer of the
stack is covered by the license most appropriate to its nature, chosen
to enforce the same copyleft philosophy across firmware, software, and
physical design alike.

| Component | License | File |

| Firmware (ESP32) | GNU Affero General Public License v3.0 | `/firmware/LICENSE` |
| Web application | GNU Affero General Public License v3.0 | `Paramo` branch `/LICENSE` |
| Hardware (PCB, schematics, 3D / STL files) | CERN Open Hardware Licence Strongly Reciprocal v2.0 | `/hardware/LICENSE` |
| Documentation and tutorials | Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0 International | `/docs/LICENSE` |

The root license of this repository is **GNU AGPL v3.0**, which GitHub
reads as the primary project license. It governs all software components.
Hardware designs are separately and explicitly governed by CERN-OHL-S v2.0
as declared in `/hardware/LICENSE`.

These licenses are complementary. AGPL covers all software layers and any
derived online services. CERN-OHL-S covers physical designs. Together they
ensure the entire stack — from PCB trace to browser interface — remains
permanently and irrevocably open.

---

## Why these licenses: the ethos of Páramo

A kiln should not be firstly perceibed as a consumer product. It is a tool built to last decades, passed
between studios, repaired by hand, adapted to the specific needs of the person
using it. The electronics and software we build around kilns should be no
different. Any action towards encouraging the right to repair, understand, recycle and upgrade is
a step towards what we deserve as communities. In any context given.

The trend in industrial and hobbyist electronics is toward the opposite:
proprietary firmware, cloud services that disappear when the business model
changes, hardware with no published schematics, and upgrade cycles designed
to make last year's device obsolete. We find this unacceptable — especially
for tools used by independent ceramic artists, small studios, and community
workshops that cannot afford to be held hostage by a vendor's pricing or
discontinuation decisions.

Páramo was built on open resources, community knowledge, and freely shared
prior work. It will remain open in return. And for that I cannot be naive.

**I chose copyleft licenses deliberately, not by default.**

Permissive licenses (MIT, Apache, BSD, CC0) allow any company to take this
work, improve it privately, and sell a closed derivative without contributing
anything back. That is a legitimate model for some projects. It is not
acceptable here. The makers and potters who might build on Páramo deserve
the same freedoms I had when I built it.

AGPL was chosen specifically because its copyleft extends to network services:
if you run a modified version of this software as an online service, you must
publish your source code. There are no silent SaaS forks. No proprietary
cloud wrappers. No "we took the open version and made it paid."

CERN-OHL-S was chosen because it is the only hardware license with genuine
strong copyleft: if you distribute hardware derived from these designs, the
schematics, PCB layouts, and fabrication files must remain open under the
same terms. No closed hardware clones.

Non-commercial clauses were deliberately avoided. They exclude community
workshops that sell kits to fund their space, makers who charge for their
labour assembling units, and educators who receive grants. The line we draw
is not against commerce — it is against closure.

---

## What you can do

- Study, modify, and build upon every part of this project
- Build your own Páramo for your kiln, your studio, your school
- Adapt it to your kiln type, your firing style, your local mains frequency
- Sell assembled units or kits, provided you keep the designs open and
  make the source available to your customers
- Teach with it, write about it, translate the documentation
- Fork it and take it in a completely different direction, provided your
  fork remains open under the same terms

## What these licenses prevent

- Closing the source code and selling a proprietary version
- Running a modified version as an online service without publishing changes
- Filing patents on methods or designs derived from this work in order to
  exclude others from implementing them
- Distributing modified hardware without publishing the modified design files
- Any form of proprietary capture of this project or its derivatives

